.SH "NAME"
dotenv \- load environment variables from .env files and execute command
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBdotenv\fP [\fB\-h\fP | \fB\-\-help\fP]
.br
\fBdotenv\fP [\fB\-x\fP | \fB\-\-exec\fP] [\fB\-s\fP | \fB\-\-strict\fP] [\fB\-q\fP | \fB\-\-silent\fP] [\fB\-e\fP \fIFILE\fP].\|.\|. \fICOMMAND\fP [\fIARGS\fP.\|.\|.]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
\fBdotenv\fP loads environment variables from one or more .env files and executes
a command with the loaded environment. It supports multiline values, quoted
strings, and comments.
.sp
Environment variables that are already set in the calling environment take
precedence over variables defined in .env files. This allows for easy
overriding of .env file values.
.sp
The .env file format follows common conventions. For detailed syntax
information, see \fBenv\fP(5).
.SH "OPTIONS"
.sp
\fB\-e\fP \fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
Specify .env file to load. Can be specified multiple times to load multiple
files. If not specified, defaults to \fB.env\fP. Files are processed in order,
with later files overriding variables from earlier files.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-x\fP, \fB\-\-exec\fP
.RS 4
Replace the current shell process with the executed command instead of
running it in a subprocess.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-s\fP, \fB\-\-strict\fP
.RS 4
Fail with exit code 1 when warnings occur (e.g., missing .env files,
unclosed quotes).
.RE
.sp
\fB\-q\fP, \fB\-\-silent\fP
.RS 4
Suppress warning messages. Does not affect error behavior.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-h\fP, \fB\-\-help\fP
.RS 4
Show help message and exit.
.RE
.SH "ARGUMENTS"
.sp
\fICOMMAND\fP
.RS 4
Command to execute with the loaded environment variables.
.RE
.sp
\fIARGS\fP.\|.\|.
.RS 4
Arguments to pass to the command.
.RE
.SH "VARIABLE PRECEDENCE"
.sp
Variables are resolved in the following order (highest to lowest precedence):
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
Environment variables set in the calling shell
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
Variables from .env files (processed in command\-line order)
.RE
.sp
This means that \fBTEST=override dotenv \-e .env command\fP will use "override" as
the value of TEST, regardless of what .env contains.
.sp
When multiple .env files are specified, later files override variables from
earlier files, but only if those variables are not already set in the
environment.
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.sp
Execute go command with environment from .env file
.RS 4
dotenv go run main.go
.RE
.sp
Load variables from multiple .env files and run Python script
.RS 4
dotenv \-e .env \-e .env.production python app.py
.RE
.sp
Use custom .env file with npm
.RS 4
dotenv \-e .env.local npm start
.RE
.sp
Override .env file value with environment variable
.RS 4
TEST=override dotenv \-e .env printenv TEST
.RE
.sp
Fail if .env.production is missing instead of just warning
.RS 4
dotenv \-s \-e .env.production python app.py
.RE
.sp
Suppress warning message about missing.env file
.RS 4
dotenv \-q \-e missing.env node server.js
.RE
.sp
Replace current shell with bash using environment from .env file
.RS 4
dotenv \-x \-e .env bash
.RE
.sp
Replace current process with Node.js server using default .env file
.RS 4
dotenv \-\-exec node server.js
.RE
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.sp
\fB0\fP
.RS 4
Success.
.RE
.sp
\fB1\fP
.RS 4
Runtime error (file not found in strict mode, parse error).
.RE
.sp
\fB2\fP
.RS 4
Usage error (missing command, invalid options).
.RE
.sp
\fBN\fP
.RS 4
Exit status of the executed command.
.RE
.SH "FILES"
.sp
\fB.env\fP
.RS 4
Default environment file if no \fB\-e\fP option is specified.
.RE
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.sp
\fBenv\fP(5), \fBenv\fP(1), \fBexport\fP(1), \fBsource\fP(1), \fBexec\fP(1)
